We use the @cache decorator to cache the results of the dfs function. This is because we are calling the function recursively, and we want to avoid recalculating the same values.
We start with the last character of the target string, and then we iterate over the indices of the character in the source string. For each index, we check if the character at that index is the same as the character at the current index in the target string. If it is, then we call the dfs function recursively with the next index. If it is not, then we add the cost of the character at the current index in the target string to the cost of the rest of the string.
